# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: point-location
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] The **doubly connected edge list** (**DCEL**), also known as **half-edge data structure**, is a data structure to represent an embedding of a planar graph in the plane, and polytopes in 3D.
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] This data structure provides efficient manipulation of the topological information associated with the objects in question (vertices, edges, faces).
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] It is used in many algorithms of computational geometry to handle polygonal subdivisions of the plane, commonly called planar straight-line graphs (PSLG).
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] For example, a Voronoi diagram is commonly represented by a DCEL inside a bounding box.
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] This data structure was originally suggested by Muller and Preparata for representations of 3D convex polyhedra.
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] Simplified versions of the data structure, as described here, only consider connected graphs, but the DCEL structure may be extended to handle disconnected graphs as well by introducing dummy edges between disconnected components.
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] DCEL is more than just a doubly linked list of edges.
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] In the general case, a DCEL contains a record for each edge, vertex and face of the subdivision.
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] Each record may contain additional information, for example, a face may contain the name of the area.
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] Each edge usually bounds two faces and it is, therefore, convenient to regard each edge as two "half-edges" (which are represented by the two edges with opposite directions, between two vertices, in the picture on the right).
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] Each half-edge is "associated" with a single face and thus has a pointer to that face.
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] *All* half-edges associated with a face are clockwise or counter-clockwise.
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] For example, in the picture on the right, all half-edges associated with the middle face (i.e. the "internal" half-edges) are counter-clockwise.
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] A half-edge has a pointer to the next half-edge and previous half-edge of the same face.
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] To reach the other face, we can go to the twin of the half-edge and then traverse the other face.
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] Each half-edge also has a pointer to its origin vertex (the destination vertex can be obtained by querying the origin of its twin, or of the next half-edge).
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] Each vertex contains the coordinates of the vertex and also stores a pointer to an arbitrary edge that has the vertex as its origin.
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] Each face stores a pointer to some half-edge of its outer boundary (if the face is unbounded then pointer is null).
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] It also has a list of half-edges, one for each hole that may be incident within the face.
[src:point-location/doubly-connected-edge-list] If the vertices or faces do not hold any interesting information, there is no need to store them, thus saving space and reducing the data structure's complexity.
[src:point-location/planar-straight-line-graph] In computational geometry and geometric graph theory, a **planar straight-line graph** (**PSLG**), also called a **straight-line plane graph** or **plane straight-line graph**, is an embedding of a planar graph in the plane such that its edges are mapped into straight-line segments.
[src:point-location/planar-straight-line-graph] Fáry's theorem (1948) states that every planar graph has this kind of embedding.
[src:point-location/planar-straight-line-graph] In computational geometry, PSLGs have often been called **planar subdivisions**, with an assumption or assertion that subdivisions are polygonal rather than having curved boundaries.
[src:point-location/planar-straight-line-graph] PSLGs may serve as representations of various maps, e.g., geographical maps in geographical information systems.
[src:point-location/planar-straight-line-graph] Special cases of PSLGs are triangulations (polygon triangulation, point-set triangulation).
[src:point-location/planar-straight-line-graph] Point-set triangulations are maximal PSLGs in the sense that it is impossible to add straight edges to them while keeping the graph planar.
[src:point-location/planar-straight-line-graph] Triangulations have numerous applications in various areas.
[src:point-location/planar-straight-line-graph] PSLGs may be seen as a special kind of Euclidean graphs.
[src:point-location/planar-straight-line-graph] However, in discussions involving Euclidean graphs, the primary interest is their metric properties, i.e., distances between vertices, while for PSLGs the primary interest is the topological properties.
[src:point-location/planar-straight-line-graph] For some graphs, such as Delaunay triangulations, both metric and topological properties are of importance.
[src:point-location/planar-straight-line-graph] There exist three well-known data structures for representing PSLGs, these are the Winged-edge data structure, Halfedge, and Quadedge.
[src:point-location/planar-straight-line-graph] The winged-edge data structure is the oldest of the three, but manipulating it often requires complicated case distinctions.
[src:point-location/planar-straight-line-graph] This is because edge references do not store the edge direction, and the directions of edges around a face need not be consistent.
[src:point-location/planar-straight-line-graph] The halfedge data structure stores both orientations of an edge and links them properly, simplifying operations and the storage scheme.
[src:point-location/planar-straight-line-graph] The Quadedge data structure stores both the planar subdivision and its dual simultaneously.
[src:point-location/planar-straight-line-graph] Its records consist explicitly only of edge records, four for each edge, and in a simplified form it is suitable for storing PSLGs.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] In computational geometry, the **point-in-polygon** (**PIP**) problem asks whether a given point in the plane lies inside, outside, or on the boundary of a polygon.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] It is a special case of point location problems and finds applications in areas that deal with processing geometrical data, such as computer graphics, computer vision, geographic information systems (GIS), motion planning, and computer-aided design (CAD).
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] An early description of the problem in computer graphics shows two common approaches (ray casting and angle summation) in use as early as 1974.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] An attempt of computer graphics veterans to trace the history of the problem and some tricks for its solution can be found in an issue of the *Ray Tracing News*.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] One simple way of finding whether the point is inside or outside a simple polygon is to test how many times a ray, starting from the point and going in any fixed direction, intersects the edges of the polygon.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] If the point is on the outside of the polygon the ray will intersect its edge an even number of times.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] If the point is on the inside of the polygon then it will intersect the edge an odd number of times.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] The status of a point on the edge of the polygon depends on the details of the ray intersection algorithm.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] This algorithm is sometimes also known as the **crossing number algorithm** or the even–odd rule **algorithm**, and was known as early as 1962.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] The algorithm is based on a simple observation that if a point moves along a ray from infinity to the probe point and if it crosses the boundary of a polygon, possibly several times, then it alternately goes from the outside to inside, then from the inside to the outside, etc.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] As a result, after every two "border crossings" the moving point goes outside.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] This observation may be mathematically proved using the Jordan curve theorem.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] If implemented on a computer with finite-precision arithmetic, the results may be incorrect if the point lies very close to that boundary, because of rounding errors.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] For some applications, like video games or other entertainment products, this is not a large concern since they often favor speed over precision.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] Most implementations of the ray casting algorithm consecutively check intersections of a ray with all sides of the polygon in turn.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] In this case the following problem must be addressed.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] If the ray passes exactly through a vertex of a polygon, then it will intersect 2 segments at their endpoints.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] While it is OK for the case of the topmost vertex in the example or the vertex between crossing 4 and 5, the case of the rightmost vertex (in the example) requires that we count one intersection for the algorithm to work correctly.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] A similar problem arises with horizontal segments that happen to fall on the ray.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] The issue is solved as follows: If the intersection point is a vertex of a tested polygon side, then the intersection counts only if the other vertex of the side lies below the ray.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] This is effectively equivalent to considering vertices *on* the ray as lying slightly *above* the ray.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] Once again, the case of the ray passing through a vertex may pose numerical problems in finite-precision arithmetic: for two sides adjacent to the same vertex the straightforward computation of the intersection with a ray may not give the vertex in both cases.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] If the polygon is specified by its vertices, then this problem is eliminated by checking the y-coordinates of the ray and the ends of the tested polygon side before actual computation of the intersection.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] In other cases, when polygon sides are computed from other types of data, other tricks must be applied for the numerical robustness of the algorithm.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] Another technique used to check if a point is inside a polygon is to compute the given point's winding number with respect to the polygon.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] If the winding number is non-zero, the point lies inside the polygon.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] This algorithm is sometimes also known as the *nonzero-rule algorithm*.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] One way to compute the winding number is to sum up the angles subtended by each side of the polygon.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] However, this involves costly inverse trigonometric functions, which generally makes this algorithm performance-inefficient (slower) compared to the ray casting algorithm.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] Luckily, these inverse trigonometric functions do not need to be computed.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] Since the result, the sum of all angles, can add up to 0 or $2\pi$ (or multiples of $2\pi$ ) only, it is sufficient to track through which quadrants the polygon winds, as it turns around the test point, which makes the winding number algorithm comparable in speed to counting the boundary crossings.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] An improved algorithm to calculate the winding number was developed by Dan Sunday in 2001.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] It does not use angles in calculations, nor any trigonometry, and functions exactly the same as the ray casting algorithms described above.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] Sunday's algorithm works by considering an infinite horizontal ray cast from the point being checked.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] Whenever that ray crosses an edge of the polygon, Juan Pineda's edge crossing algorithm (1988) is used to determine how the crossing will affect the winding number.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] As Sunday describes it, if the edge crosses the ray going "upwards", the winding number is incremented; if it crosses the ray "downwards", the number is decremented.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] Sunday's algorithm gives the correct answer for nonsimple polygons, whereas the boundary crossing algorithm fails in this case.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] Similar methods are used in SVG for defining a way of filling with color various shapes (such as path, polyline, polygon, text etc.).
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] The algorithm of filling is influenced by 'fill-rule' attribute.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] The value may be either `nonzero` or `evenodd`.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] For example, in a pentagram, there is a central "hole" (visible background) with `evenodd`, and none with `nonzero` attribute.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] For simple polygons, the algorithms will give the same result.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] However, for complex polygons, the algorithms may give different results for points in the regions where the polygon intersects itself, where the polygon does not have a clearly defined inside and outside.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] One solution using the even-odd rule is to transform (complex) polygons into simpler ones that are even-odd-equivalent before the intersection check.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] This, however, is computationally expensive.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] It is less expensive to use the fast non-zero winding number algorithm, which gives the correct result even when the polygon overlaps itself.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] The point in polygon problem may be considered in the general repeated geometric query setting: given a single polygon and a sequence of query points, quickly find the answers for each query point.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] Clearly, any of the general approaches for planar point location may be used.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] Simpler solutions are available for some special polygons.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] Simpler algorithms are possible for monotone polygons, star-shaped polygons, convex polygons and triangles.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] The triangle case can be solved easily by use of a barycentric coordinate system, parametric equation or dot product.
[src:point-location/point-in-polygon] The dot product method extends naturally to any convex polygon.
[src:point-location/point-location] The **point location** class of problems is a fundamental topic of computational geometry.
[src:point-location/point-location] It finds applications in areas that deal with processing geometrical data: computer graphics, geographic information systems (GIS), motion planning, and computer aided design (CAD).
[src:point-location/point-location] In one of its general forms, the problem is, given a partition of the space into disjoint regions, to determine the region where a query point lies.
[src:point-location/point-location] A special case is the point in polygon problem, in which one needs to determine whether a point is inside, outside, or on the boundary of a single polygon.
[src:point-location/point-location] The problem may be stated for a set of arbitrary regions in space, not necessarily disjoint and not necessarily constituting a partition.
[src:point-location/point-location] Further, one may need to determine the location of several points with respect to the same partition of the space.
[src:point-location/point-location] Or, alternatively, partitions may be changing.
[src:point-location/point-location] In the latter case the class of problems overlaps with range search problems.
[src:point-location/point-location] To solve the problems with varying queries or regions efficiently, it is useful to build a data structure that, given a query point, quickly determines which region contains the query point (e.g. the Voronoi diagram).
[src:point-location/point-location] In the planar case, we are given a planar subdivision *S*, formed by multiple polygons called faces, and need to determine which face contains a query point.
[src:point-location/point-location] A brute force search of each face using the point-in-polygon algorithm is possible, but usually not feasible for subdivisions of high complexity.
[src:point-location/point-location] Several different approaches lead to optimal data structures, with O(*n*) storage space and O(log *n*) query time, where *n* is the total number of vertices in *S*.
[src:point-location/point-location] For simplicity, we assume that the planar subdivision is contained inside a square bounding box.
[src:point-location/point-location] The simplest and earliest data structure to achieve O(log *n*) time was discovered by Dobkin and Lipton in 1976.
[src:point-location/point-location] It is based on subdividing *S* using vertical lines that pass through each vertex in *S*.
[src:point-location/point-location] The region between two consecutive vertical lines is called a slab.
[src:point-location/point-location] Notice that each slab is divided by non-intersecting line segments that completely cross the slab from left to right.
[src:point-location/point-location] The region between two consecutive segments inside a slab corresponds to a unique face of *S*.
[src:point-location/point-location] Given a slab subdivided into regions by non-intersecting segments that completely cross the slab from left to right, determine which region contains a given point.
[src:point-location/point-location] The first problem can be solved by binary search on the *x* coordinate of the vertical lines in O(log *n*) time.
[src:point-location/point-location] The second problem can also be solved in O(log *n*) time by binary search.
[src:point-location/point-location] To see how, notice that, as the segments do not intersect and completely cross the slab, the segments can be sorted vertically inside each slab.
[src:point-location/point-location] While this algorithm allows point location in logarithmic time and is easy to implement, the space required to build the slabs and the regions contained within the slabs can be as high as O(*n*²), since each slab can cross a significant fraction of the segments.
[src:point-location/point-location] Several authors noticed that the segments that cross two adjacent slabs are mostly the same.
[src:point-location/point-location] Therefore, the size of the data structure can be significantly reduced.
[src:point-location/point-location] More specifically, Sarnak and Tarjan sweep a vertical line *l* from left to right over the plane, while maintaining the segments that intersect *l* in a Persistent red-black tree.
[src:point-location/point-location] This allows them to reduce the storage space to O(*n*), while maintaining the O(log *n*) query time.
[src:point-location/point-location] A (vertical) monotone chain is a path such that the *y*-coordinate never increases along the path.
[src:point-location/point-location] A simple polygon is (vertical) monotone if it is formed by two monotone chains, with the first and last vertices in common.
[src:point-location/point-location] It is possible to add some edges to a planar subdivision, in order to make all faces monotone, obtaining what is called a monotone subdivision.
[src:point-location/point-location] This process does not add any vertices to the subdivision (therefore, the size remains O(*n*)), and can be performed in O(*n* log *n*) time by plane sweep (it can also be performed in linear time, using polygon triangulation).
[src:point-location/point-location] Therefore, there is no loss of generality, if we restrict our data structure to the case of monotone subdivisions, as we do in this section.
[src:point-location/point-location] The weakness of the slab decomposition is that the vertical lines create additional segments in the decomposition, making it difficult to achieve O(*n*) storage space.
[src:point-location/point-location] Guibas, and Jorge Stolfi discovered an optimal data structure that only uses the edges in a monotone subdivision.
[src:point-location/point-location] The idea is to use vertical monotone chains, instead of using vertical lines to partition the subdivision.
[src:point-location/point-location] Converting this general idea to an actual efficient data structure is not a simple task.
[src:point-location/point-location] First, we need to be able to compute a monotone chain that divides the subdivision into two halves of similar sizes.
[src:point-location/point-location] Second, since some edges may be contained in several monotone chains, we need to be careful to guarantee that the storage space is O(n).
[src:point-location/point-location] Third, testing whether a point is on the left or the right side of a monotone subdivision takes O(*n*) time if performed naïvely.
[src:point-location/point-location] Details on how to solve the first two issues are beyond the scope of this article.
[src:point-location/point-location] We briefly mention how to address the third issue.
[src:point-location/point-location] Using binary search, we can test whether a point is to the left or right of a monotone chain in O(log *n*) time.
[src:point-location/point-location] As we need to perform another nested binary search through O(log *n*) chains to actually determine the point location, the query time is O(log² n).
[src:point-location/point-location] To achieve O(log *n*) query time, we need to use fractional cascading, keeping pointers between the edges of different monotone chains.
[src:point-location/point-location] A polygon with *m* vertices can be partitioned into *m*–2 triangles.
[src:point-location/point-location] Which can be shown by induction starting from a triangle.
[src:point-location/point-location] There are numerous algorithms to triangulate a polygon efficiently, the fastest having O(*n*) worst case time.
[src:point-location/point-location] Therefore, we can decompose each polygon of our subdivision in triangles, and restrict our data structure to the case of subdivisions formed exclusively by triangles.
[src:point-location/point-location] Kirkpatrick gives a data structure for point location in triangulated subdivisions with O(*n*) storage space and O(log *n*) query time.
[src:point-location/point-location] The general idea is to build a hierarchy of triangles.
[src:point-location/point-location] To perform a query, we start by finding the top-level triangle that contains the query point.
[src:point-location/point-location] Since the number of top-level triangles is bounded by a constant, this operation can be performed in O(1) time.
[src:point-location/point-location] Each triangle has pointers to the triangles it intersects in the next level of the hierarchy, and the number of pointers is also bounded by a constant.
[src:point-location/point-location] We proceed with the query by finding which triangle contains the query point level by level.
[src:point-location/point-location] The data structure is built in the opposite order, that is, bottom-up.
[src:point-location/point-location] We start with the triangulated subdivision, and choose an independent set of vertices to be removed.
[src:point-location/point-location] After removing the vertices, we retriangulate the subdivision.
[src:point-location/point-location] Because the subdivision is formed by triangles, a greedy algorithm can find an independent set that contains a constant fraction of the vertices.
[src:point-location/point-location] Therefore, the number of removal steps is O(log *n*).
[src:point-location/point-location] A randomized approach to this problem is based on trapezoidal decomposition, or trapezoidal map.
[src:point-location/point-location] A trapezoidal decomposition is obtained by shooting vertical bullets going both up and down from each vertex in the original subdivision.
[src:point-location/point-location] The bullets stop when they hit an edge, and form a new edge in the subdivision.
[src:point-location/point-location] This way, we obtain a subset of the slab decomposition, with only O(*n*) edges and vertices, since for each vertex in the original subdivision we only add two new vertices and increase the number of edges by four.
[src:point-location/point-location] A trapezoidal decomposition can be constructed by adding the segments from the original subdivision, one by one, in a random order.
[src:point-location/point-location] Initially (before no segments have been added) the trapezoidal decomposition consists of a single trapezoid, the bounding box of the subdivision.
[src:point-location/point-location] The point locations in the current subdivision, performed within this algorithm, may be done using the same structure that, at the end of the algorithm, can be used for point location queries in the final trapezoidal decomposition.
[src:point-location/point-location] This point location data structure takes the form of a directed acyclic graph, where the vertices are the trapezoids that existed at some point in the refinement, and directed edges connect each trapezoid that is no longer in the refinement to the trapezoids that replaced it.
[src:point-location/point-location] A point location query is performed by following a path in this graph, starting from the initial trapezoid, and at each step choosing the replacement trapezoid that contains the query point, until reaching a trapezoid that has not been replaced.
[src:point-location/point-location] The expected depth of a search in this digraph, starting from any query point, is O(log *n*).
[src:point-location/point-location] The space for the data structure is proportional to the number of trapezoids created throughout this refinement process, which in expectation is O(*n*).
[src:point-location/point-location] There are no known general point location data structures with linear space and logarithmic query time for dimensions greater than 2.
[src:point-location/point-location] Therefore, we need to sacrifice either query time, or storage space, or restrict ourselves to some less general type of subdivision.
[src:point-location/point-location] In three-dimensional space, it is possible to answer point location queries in O(log² *n*) using O(*n* log *n*) space.
[src:point-location/point-location] The general idea is to maintain several planar point location data structures, corresponding to the intersection of the subdivision with *n* parallel planes that contain each subdivision vertex.
[src:point-location/point-location] A naive use of this idea would increase the storage space to O(*n*²).
[src:point-location/point-location] In the same fashion as in the slab decomposition, the similarity between consecutive data structures can be exploited in order to reduce the storage space to O(*n* log *n*), but the query time increases to O(log² *n*).
[src:point-location/point-location] In *d*-dimensional space, point location can be solved by recursively projecting the faces into a (*d*-1)-dimensional space.
[src:point-location/point-location] While the query time is O(log *n*), the storage space can be as high as $O(n^{2^{d}})$ .
[src:point-location/point-location] The high complexity of the *d*-dimensional data structures led to the study of special types of subdivision.
[src:point-location/point-location] One important example is the case of arrangements of hyperplanes.
[src:point-location/point-location] An arrangement of *n* hyperplanes defines O(*nd*) cells, but point location can be performed in O(log *n*) time with O(*nd*) space by using Chazelle's hierarchical cuttings.
[src:point-location/point-location] Another special type of subdivision is called rectilinear (or orthogonal) subdivision.
[src:point-location/point-location] In a rectilinear subdivision, all edges are parallel to one of the *d* orthogonal axis.
[src:point-location/point-location] In this case, point location can be answered in O(log*d*-1 *n*) time with O(*n*) space.
[src:point-location/search-data-structure] In computer science, a **search data structure** is any data structure that allows the efficient retrieval of specific items from a set of items, such as a specific record from a database.
[src:point-location/search-data-structure] The simplest, most general, and least efficient search structure is merely an unordered sequential list of all the items.
[src:point-location/search-data-structure] Locating the desired item in such a list, by the linear search method, inevitably requires a number of operations proportional to the number *n* of items, in the worst case as well as in the average case.
[src:point-location/search-data-structure] Useful search data structures allow faster retrieval; however, they are limited to queries of some specific kind.
[src:point-location/search-data-structure] Moreover, since the cost of building such structures is at least proportional to *n*, they only pay off if several queries are to be performed on the same database (or on a database that changes little between queries).
[src:point-location/search-data-structure] The simplest kind of query is to locate a record that has a specific field (the *key*) equal to a specified value *v*.
[src:point-location/search-data-structure] Other common kinds of query are "find the item with smallest (or largest) key value", "find the item with largest key value not exceeding *v*", "find all items with key values between specified bounds *v*min and *v*max".
[src:point-location/search-data-structure] In certain databases the key values may be points in some multi-dimensional space.
[src:point-location/search-data-structure] For example, the key may be a geographic position (latitude and longitude) on the Earth.
[src:point-location/search-data-structure] In that case, common kinds of queries are "find the record with a key closest to a given point *v*", or "find all items whose key lies at a given distance from *v*", or "find all items within a specified region *R* of the space".
[src:point-location/search-data-structure] A common special case of the latter are simultaneous range queries on two or more simple keys, such as "find all employee records with salary between 50,000 and 100,000 and hired between 1995 and 2007".
[src:point-location/search-data-structure] This table is only an approximate summary; for each data structure there are special situations and variants that may lead to different costs.
[src:point-location/search-data-structure] Also two or more data structures can be combined to obtain lower costs.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] In graph theory, **trapezoid graphs** are intersection graphs of trapezoids between two horizontal lines.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] They are a class of co-comparability graphs that contain interval graphs and permutation graphs as subclasses.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] A graph is a **trapezoid graph** if there exists a set of trapezoids corresponding to the vertices of the graph such that two vertices are joined by an edge if and only if the corresponding trapezoids intersect.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Trapezoid graphs were introduced by Dagan, Golumbic, and Pinter in 1988.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] There exists ${O}(n\log n)$ algorithms for chromatic number, weighted independent set, clique cover, and maximum weighted clique.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Given a channel, a pair of two horizontal lines, a trapezoid between these lines is defined by two points on the top and two points on the bottom line.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] A graph is a trapezoid graph if there exists a set of trapezoids corresponding to the vertices of the graph such that two vertices are joined by an edge if and only if the corresponding trapezoids intersect.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] The interval order dimension of a partially ordered set, *P* = (*X*, <), is the minimum number d of interval orders *P*1 … *Pd* such that *P* = *P*1 ∩ … ∩ *Pd*.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] The incomparability graph of a partially ordered set *P* = (*X*, <) is the undirected graph *G* = (*X*, *E*) where x is adjacent to y in G if and only if x and y are incomparable in P.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] An undirected graph is a trapezoid graph if and only if it is the incomparability graph of a partial order having interval order dimension at most 2.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] The problems of finding maximum cliques and of coloring trapezoid graphs are connected to channel routing problems in VLSI design.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Given some labeled terminals on the upper and lower side of a two-sided channel, terminals with the same label will be connected in a common net.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] This net can be represented by a trapezoid containing the rightmost terminals and leftmost terminals with the same label.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Nets may be routed without intersection if and only if the corresponding trapezoids do not intersect.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Therefore, the number of layers needed to route the nets without intersection is equal to the graph’s chromatic number.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Trapezoids can be used to represent a trapezoid graph by using the definition of trapezoid graph.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] A trapezoid graph's trapezoid representation can be seen in Figure 1.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Dominating rectangles, or box representation, maps the points on the lower of the two lines of the trapezoid representation as lying on the x-axis and that of the upper line as lying on the y-axis of the Euclidean plane.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Each trapezoid then corresponds to an axis-parallel box in the plane.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Using the notion of a dominance order (In ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{K}$ ⁠, x is said to be dominated by y, denoted *x* < *y*, if xi is less than yi for *i* = 1, …, *k*), we say that a box b dominates a box b’ if the lower corner of b dominates the upper corner of b’.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Furthermore, if one of two boxes dominates the other we say that they are comparable.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Thus, two trapezoids are disjoint exactly if their corresponding boxes are comparable.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] The box representation is useful because the associated dominance order allows sweep line algorithms to be used.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Bitolerance graphs are incomparability graphs of a bitolerance order.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] In 1993, Langley showed that the bounded bitolerance graphs are equivalent to the class of trapezoid graphs.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] The class of trapezoid graphs properly contains the union of interval and permutation graphs and is equivalent to the incomparability graphs of partially ordered sets having interval order dimension at most two.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Permutation graphs can be seen as the special case of trapezoid graphs when every trapezoid has zero area.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] This occurs when both of the trapezoid’s points on the upper channel are in the same position and both points on the lower channel are in the same position.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Like all incomparability graphs, trapezoid graphs are perfect.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Circle trapezoid graphs are a class of graphs proposed by Felsner et al. in 1993.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] They are a superclass of the trapezoid graph class, and also contain circle graphs and circular-arc graphs.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] A circle trapezoid is the region in a circle that lies between two non-crossing chords and a circle trapezoid graph is the intersection graph of families of circle trapezoids on a common circle.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] There is an $O(n^{2})$ algorithm for maximum weighted independent set problem and an ${O}(n^{2}\log n)$ algorithm for the maximum weighted clique problem.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Algorithms for trapezoid graphs should be compared with algorithms for general co-comparability graphs.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] For this larger class of graphs, the maximum independent set and the minimum clique cover problem can be solved in ${O}(n^{2}\log n)$ time.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Dagan et al. first proposed an ${O}(nk)$ algorithm for coloring trapezoid graphs, where n is the number of nodes and k is the chromatic number of the graph.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Later, using the box representation of trapezoid graphs, Felsner published ${O}(n\log n)$ algorithms for chromatic number, weighted independent set, clique cover, and maximum weighted clique.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] These algorithms all require ${O}(n)$ space.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] These algorithms rely on the associated dominance in the box representation that allows sweeping line algorithms to be used.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Felsner proposes using balanced trees that can do insert, delete, and query operations in ${O}(\log n)$ time, which results in ${O}(n\log n)$ algorithms.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] To determine if a graph ${G}$ is a trapezoid graph, search for a transitive orientation ${F}$ on the complement of ${G}$ .
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Since trapezoid graphs are a subset of co-comparability graphs, if ${G}$ is a trapezoid graph, its complement ${G'}$ must be a comparability graph.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] If a transitive orientation ${F}$ of the complement ${G'}$ does not exist, ${G}$ is not a trapezoid graph.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] If ${F}$ does exist, test to see if the order given by ${F}$ is a trapezoid order.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] The fastest algorithm for trapezoid order recognition was proposed by McConnell and Spinrad in 1994, with a running time of $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] The process reduces the interval dimension 2 question to a problem of covering an associated bipartite graph by chain graphs (graphs with no induced 2K2).
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] Using vertex splitting, the recognition problem for trapezoid graphs was shown by Mertzios and Corneil to succeed in $O(n(n+m))$ time, where m denotes the number of edges.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] This process involves augmenting a given graph ${G}$ , and then transforming the augmented graph by replacing each of the original graph’s vertices by a pair of new vertices.
[src:point-location/trapezoid-graph] This “split graph” is a permutation graph with special properties if an only if ${G}$ is a trapezoid graph.
